Status: Research & Experimental
Focus: Data formats, resilience, cognitive alignment, systems architecture

ğŸŒŸ Overview

Lichen OS is an experimental cognitive systems architecture exploring how data structure, error correction, and coherence metrics can improve the robustness and alignment of future AI systems.

Rather than optimizing for human-facing software, Lichen OS focuses on machine-native representations designed to:

detect non-legitimate state changes,

preserve contextual integrity,

and reduce systemic drift under stress.

ğŸ”‘ Core Concepts
FC-496 â€” Fixed-Structure Cognitive Data Cells

FC-496 is a 496-bit fixed-size data cell where:

All bits are structurally allocated

No bit is informationally neutral

Any modification propagates measurable changes across the cell

This design means that unauthorized or incoherent modifications cannot be injected silently â€” changes are detectable, even when partially corrected.

âš ï¸ FC-496 does not claim to make fraud impossible.
It aims to make illegitimate changes non-transparent and observable.

Key features:

Fixed-size atomic cells (496 bits)

Parallel BCH(31,16) error correction

Structural coupling between metadata and payload

Designed for stress and corruption detection, not secrecy

UICT â€” Unified Information Compression Theory (Research)

UICT explores the hypothesis that information compression and physical structure are linked.

Within Lichen OS, UICT is treated as:

a modeling framework, not a physical law

a way to reason about coherence, redundancy, and stability

UICT components are isolated and optional, allowing independent evaluation.

